    "The family friend and neighbor, the artist Reginald Marsh, encouraged Goodrich to paint.": [],
    "Goodrich graduated from high school in 1913 and studied at the Art Students League in New York, arriving early enough to witness the Armory Show, and later studying at the National Academy of Design (also in New York) through 1918.": [],
    "Goodrich gave up painting that year, working in the steel business and editing books at Macmillan Company through 1923.": [],
    "He married Edith Havens in 1924 and began writing for <em>The Arts</em>, a popular cultural magazine.": [],
    "He soon became an associate editor, authoring articles on American and European art and art exhibitions as well as contributing seminal reassessments of American art such as the Hudson River School, Winslow Homer and the young artist Edward Hopper.": [],
    "Betweeen 1927 and 1928, Goodrich and his wife traveled to Europe.": [
